Setup

Before introducing the exercises, we will need to make sure that the relevant data objects have been loaded.

de_treated <- readRDS("Robjects/de_treated.rds")
dds <- readRDS("Robjects/dds.rds")

Plotting multiple genes

The first exercise involves plotting the expression level of multiple genes. As we saw, plotCounts is only able to plot one gene.

The code to plot multiple genes is a bit more involved, and we will start by normalizing the counts. We do not usually need to perform this steps as it happens automatically when the DESeq function is run.

library(DESeq2)
dds <- estimateSizeFactors(dds)
count_matrix <- counts(dds, normalized=TRUE)

Next, we extract the ENSEMBL names of the top 10 most differentially-expressed genes.

library(dplyr)
my_genes <- results(de_treated,tidy=TRUE) %>% 
  arrange(padj) %>% 
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  pull(row)

As we saw, the count matrix is a numeric matrix rather than a data frame. We have to convert it into a data frame in order to use the standard dplyr tools. It does not have the gene names as a column and an easy way to add them is to use the rownames_to_column function in tibble.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes)

The data are in the wrong format to be plotting in ggplot2, so need to be converted to long or "tidy format.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count")
NA

We would like to join this data with the meta data

sampleInfo <- data.frame(colData(dds))
sampleInfo

However, the Run column in our counts matrix has an X character before each name (e.g.X1_CTR_BC_2 rather than 1_CTR_BC_2). This is because column names in a numeric matrix are no allowed to begin with a number. We can use a function to replace the X with an empty character; effectively deleting the X.

count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count") %>% 
  mutate(Run = stringr::str_replace_all(Run, "X",""))

The count data can now be joined with the sample information to create a data frame ready for plotting in ggplot2.

plot_data <- count_matrix %>% data.frame %>% 
  tibble::rownames_to_column("row") %>% 
  filter(row %in% my_genes) %>% 
  tidyr::pivot_longer(-row, names_to = "Run",values_to = "count") %>% 
  mutate(Run = stringr::str_replace_all(Run, "X","")) %>%
  left_join(sampleInfo)
Joining, by = "Run"

Analysing a subset of data, or using a multi-factor analysis

As we saw in the workshop, it is possible to analyse a subset of the data, or to employ a multi-factor model to correct for technical differences in the data.
